'''Michael Kanin''' (February 1, 1910 – March 12, 1993) was an American [[film director|director]], [[film producer|producer]], [[playwright]] and [[screenwriter]] who shared an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] with [[Ring Lardner Jr.]] in 1942 for writing the [[Katharine Hepburn]]-[[Spencer Tracy]] film comedy ''[[Woman of the Year]]''.<ref name="nytobit">Collins, Glenn (March 16, 1993). "Michael Kanin, 83, Film Writer For Hepburn and Tracy, Is Dead." ''[[New York Times]]''.</ref>

Born in [[Rochester, New York]], his first job was writing and acting in [[Catskills]] resort shows with his brother [[Garson Kanin]]. In 1939, he was signed to a screenwriting contract at [[RKO]]. He married RKO co-worker [[Fay Kanin|Fay Mitchell]] in 1940, and collaborated with her on many projects, notably ''[[The Outrage]]''. Together, they received an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] nomination for ''[[Teacher's Pet (1958 film)|Teacher's Pet]]'' (1958).

